Strictly speaking, the `Map` interface in java does not have a method for sequential access.
So you can&#39;t take &quot;x first elements&quot; from a map - there&#39;s no order between them.
Some implementations do have guaranteed ordering - SortedMap (sorted by keys) and LinkedHashMap (sorted by order of insertion). 

In these cases, you can use the `entryMap()` method.

So (assuming n is the size of both maps) if you want to take x element from the first and y elements from the second you could create two iterators and take from them, something like:

    int c = rand.nextInt(n);
    Iterator&lt;Entry&lt;String, Integer&gt;&gt; i1 = x.entrySet().iterator();
    Iterator&lt;Entry&lt;String, Integer&gt;&gt; i2 = y.entrySet().iterator();
    int i = 0;
    Map&lt;Integer, String&gt; child = new HashMap&lt;String, Integer&gt;();
    Entry&lt;String, Integer&gt; e1, e2;
    while (i &lt; n)
    { 
       if (i &lt; c) {
         e1= i1.next();
         e2 = i2.next();
         child.add(e1.getKey(), e1.getValue());
       }
       else
       {
         e2 = i2.next();
         child.add(e2.getKey(), e2.getValue());
       }
       i++;
    }

