In UML, you would represent this with an **association** between `Example` and `Thing`: 

* Purists would suggest the [dot notation][1] and put a tiny dot on the `Thing` end: this tells that `Example` owns the end of the association. Not all the modelling tools support this notation.   
* Since the instance of `Example` would always know the instance of `Thing` but probably not the opposite, you&#39;d want to show this association navigable (open arrow at the end).  

The association implies the dependency.  So you should not add a redundant dependency to the diagram. A dependency without association would look like:  

    public class Example {
        Thing thing = new Thing();             // Example is associated to Thing
    
        public void method(AnotherThing x) {   // Example depends on AnotherThing
                ...;
        }
    }


  [1]: https://www.omg.org/ocup-2/documents/getting_it_right_on_the_dot.pdf

